!WIKI
Laplace transform notes
!keywords: Laplace; transfer function; system analysis

On this page I am collecting information and notes regarding the Laplace transform and it's possible application to the analysis of the frequency transfer of neuronal systems.

<h3>Definition of the Laplace transform</h3>
The Laplace transform transforms a function of a real variable (time) to a function of a complex variable (complex frequency):
$$ \mathcal{L}: t \mapsto s; t \in \mathbb{R}, s \in \mathbb{C}$$

The forward Laplace transform of a function $f(t)$ is denoted as $\mathcal{L}\{f\}(s)$, indicating the independent variable of the transform $s$, and is defined as:
$$ \mathcal{L}\{f\}(s) = \int_0^{\infty} f(t) \mathcal{e}^{-st} dt$$
(The function $f$ must be locally integratable on $[0, \infty)$)

The inverse Laplace transform $\mathcal{L}\{F\}(t)$ gives back a function of the real-valued variable:
$$ \mathcal{L}\{F\}(t) = \frac{1}{2 \pi \mathcal{i}} \lim_{T \to \infty} \int_{\gamma-\mathcal{i}T}^{\gamma+\mathcal{i}T} \mathcal{e}^{st}F(s) ds; \gamma \in \mathbb{R} $$
